Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic) Data Set¶

by Yosef Cohen¶

Investigation Overview¶

Can we identify malignancy by parameters like shape and size ?

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset is from kaggle.
Features in the data set are computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image.

There are 569 rows (cases) in the DB.¶

every case has a diagnosis -¶

M - for malingnant.¶

B - for benign.¶

every case have data about the size and the shape of the tumor.¶

on the analysis we put our focus on the features:¶

1 radius_mean    
2 texture_mean    
3 perimeter_mean   
4 area_mean    
5 smoothness_mean     
6 compactness_mean     
7 concavity_mean     
8 concave points_mean     
9 symmetry_mean     
10 fractal_dimension_mean

Note that the above cells have been set as "Skip"-type slides. That means that when the notebook is rendered as http slides, those cells won't show up.

Diagnosis¶

How many malingnant and benign we have in the dataset ?

The most cases in the dataset (above 60%) are benign.¶

Connection between features and malingnancy:¶

radius_mean and diagnosis¶

* we could see here overlapping between B & M.
* we could see that the overlapping is only on part of the range.
* we could see that the min,max,IQR, and the average are different between two plots.
* we could see outliers.

compactness_mean and diagnosis:¶

* we could see here overlapping between B & M.
* we could see that the overlapping is only on part of the range.
* we could see that the min,max,IQR, and the average are different between two plots.
* we could see outliers.

'concave points_mean' and diagnosis:¶

* we could see here overlapping between B & M.
* we could see that the overlapping is only on part of the range.
* we could see that the min,max,IQR, and the average are different between two plots.
* we could see outliers.

in comparison to the former parameters, here we see another parameter.¶

you could see that it isn't a good parameter to destinguish between B & M.¶

by the end, my conclusion is:¶

1. there is a overlap in all the parameters.¶

the overlap in some of them is small enough that we¶

could find parameters to distinguish between malingnant and benign.¶

2. the good variables to distinguish are:¶

    * all the size variables - radius, area, perimeter.
    * compactness
    * concavity
    * concave points

3. variables which are not good enough are:¶

    * smoothness
    * symmetry
    * fractal dimetion

What happens if we combine together some features ?¶

is our abillity to destinguish between B & M improves ?¶

radius_mean vs concave points_mean¶

we could see in the plot that there is a small overlapping, but the combination of this two variables gives us pretty good ability to distinguish between B & M¶

concave points_mean vs compactness_mean¶

we could see in the plot that there is a small overlapping, but the combination of this two variables gives us pretty good ability to distinguish between B & M¶

"radius_mean" vs "smoothness_mean"¶

Unlike previous examples this isn't a good combination. the difference here comes mainly from the x axis, and not from the "smoothness" parameter.¶

Conclusion:¶

  • I think that the best predictable variables are:
    1. size variables (radius,perimeter,area) - they are proportional so i prefer them as 1 variable.
    2. compactness
    3. concave points_mean & concavity - they are proportional too.
  • the combination of this 3 could predict if the tumor is malingnant or benign

the analysis of the proportions between variables is inside the full exploration analysis.¶
